title: ASX to slip, Wall St closes higher, $A leaps
summary: Australian shares are poised for an opening loss in a short New Year's Eve session. Wall Street closed modestly higher.
author: Timothy Moore

title: ASX to open lower, Wall St turns negative, $A rises
summary: Australian shares are set to open lower, taking direction from New York where early gains reversed. $A tops US76¢.

title: ASX to rise, techs pace Wall St to closing records

title: ASX to rise on overseas gains, $A recovers

title: ASX to rise, taking direction from Europe
summary: Australian shares are set to open higher, apparently with a focus on overnight gains in Europe. Apple soars on car news, Tesla slumps. Iron ore retreats.
author: Timothy Moore

title: ASX to drop as UK virus triggers global sell-off
summary: Australian shares are poised to drop at the open, following 'rational' selling in Europe, and the US, as investors assess the impact of a new virus strain in the UK.
author: Timothy Moore

title: ASX to slip on Wall St pause, iron ore leaps higher
summary: Australian shares are set to slip at the open as NSW struggles to control a virus outbreak and after Wall Street ended its week on a down note.

title: ASX poised for flat open, Wall St rallies
summary: Australian shares are set to open little changed even as US stocks, iron ore, gold and oil advance. The Australian dollar leapt still higher.

title: ASX to rise; MYEFO and labour force pending

title: ASX to open flat after markets come down to earth

summary: Australian shares are set to fall as Wall Street hit a dead end, with the S&P 500 flat despite a surge in crude and iron ore.

summary: Australian shares are set to drop as markets slipped away from all-time highs, though appetite for IPOs still burned brightly.

title: ASX to rise, iron ore tops $US145 a tonne

title: ASX to slip, Wall St stumbles late, Tesla gets Goldman lift

author: Timothy Moore

title: ASX to rise, stimulus hopes bolster US stocks

title: ASX to slip, Wall St lower after month-long rally
summary: Australian shares are set for a modest decline at the open, amid overseas weakness. Spot price of iron ore tops $US131 a tonne. RBA policy decision ahead.
author: Timothy Moore
